metadata.name: Antiflow #36
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." - Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about how opposing forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental law of nature baked into the very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.

metadata.name: Mur #279
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Omega Point #110
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: fx_dungeon #82
metadata.description:
Welcome to the fx_dungeon. Every cartridge comes loaded with a random amount of levels between 2 (common) and 7 (rare). Your goal is to collect all the coins that are disseminated around the level. Each cartridge comes with the total amount of coins that can be collected displayed on the front. 

Token levels are generated from the transaction hash and are never the same between different tokens. Scattered around the levels are also some random amount of decorative props. There are different types of props, and I added those to the features as well.

Finally, each cartridge comes in different conditions. You could get one in perfect conditions, or one that's been used over and over. Don't worry, each cartridge has been tested and it's working properly anyways!!

This is just a simple game I made learning how to code for creative projects. It's also rumored that's a Golden Edition of this cartridge can be obtained somehow..

## Controls
- Move the player around using WASD or the arrow keys. Interact with stairs using SPACEBAR or E
- You can click the image to toggle sound on or off

## Credits
- I'm using p5js and I also tweaked to my needs a tutorial from Daniel Schiffman about raycasting
- The ambient music is from Joshua McLean, it's called Mountain Trials (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L_OYo2RS8iU&list=PLwJjxqYuirCLkq42mGw4XKGQlpZSfxsYd&index=8) and it's released under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license

metadata.name: Fictional Cityscapes #70
metadata.description:
Some of the most stunning, and beloved, images are large cities, viewed from afar at the right angle, and preferably with some water in front. 

This project comes from my experiments with line art, and is slightly inspired by Hevey's amazing Dencity drop, which is on a different level to most generative art. 

The cities here are based on some fictional tower architecture and some unusual skies.
